== 2. Risk Analyst / Senior Risk Analyst

=== Hierarchy Level
2-5 years of experience, increasing independence and specialized expertise

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Independent Risk Analysis*: Leading complex risk assessments, stress testing, scenario design
- *Model Governance*: Reviewing and challenging pricing and risk models, leading validation projects
- *Limit Framework*: Proposing limit changes, designing new limit structures for new products
- *Senior Trader Interaction*: Building relationships with desk heads, influencing risk-taking decisions
- *Regulatory Engagement*: Supporting APRA examinations, preparing regulatory submissions
- *Risk Reporting*: Presenting to risk committees, preparing board-level risk reports
- *Team Leadership*: Mentoring junior analysts, reviewing their work

=== Required Skills Development

Beyond junior analyst skills:
- *Deep Product Knowledge*: Expert understanding of derivatives, structured products, trading strategies
- *Risk Judgment*: Knowing when to escalate concerns, how to balance risk control with business enablement
- *Stakeholder Management*: Influencing senior traders and executives without direct authority
- *Advanced Analytics*: Sophisticated modeling, machine learning for risk prediction, advanced statistical methods
- *Regulatory Expertise*: Deep knowledge of Basel III, FRTB, APRA standards

=== Typical Work Patterns
Work balance shifts toward analysis and stakeholder management (40-45%), with continued calculations (30-35%), model work (15-20%), and committee/reporting (10-15%). Leading stress testing projects, designing new risk frameworks, presenting to senior management.

=== Day in the Life - Senior Analyst

Similar structure to junior analyst but with strategic responsibility. Typical day includes:
- Leading monthly risk committee meeting with desk heads and CRO
- Designing new stress scenario for emerging risk (e.g., crypto market contagion)
- Challenging quant team on new exotic options pricing model
- Presenting quarterly VaR backtesting results to board risk committee
- Mentoring junior analyst on limit monitoring methodology

Hours typically 6:30am-6pm with occasional extension to 7pm during month-end or regulatory examinations.

=== Career Progression
*Within 2-3 years*: Market Risk Manager role leading team or product area, or specialization as model validation expert, regulatory capital specialist.

