== Key Insights for University Students

=== Is Sales & Trading Risk Management Right For You?

*You'll likely enjoy this career if you:*
- Love quantitative analysis and problem-solving with real-world impact
- Enjoy understanding markets and trading strategies
- Value independent thinking and professional skepticism
- Appreciate balance of technical work and business interaction
- Want to be "in the middle of the action" but not taking risk yourself
- Thrive on daily variety (market events create new challenges)
- Value work-life balance compared to front office trading
- Are comfortable challenging senior people when appropriate

*You might find it challenging if you:*
- Prefer pure research over business application
- Want to take risk and generate P&L (not monitor others doing so)
- Dislike daily operational tasks and tight deadlines
- Are uncomfortable with conflict (must challenge traders)
- Prefer creative, unstructured work over defined processes
- Want entrepreneurial role (risk management is governance-focused)

=== Skills to Develop at University

*Technical:*
- Strong mathematics (statistics, probability, calculus, linear algebra)
- Programming skills (Python essential, R useful)
- Advanced Excel (modeling, data analysis, VBA)
- Finance and derivatives theory
- Understanding of risk metrics (VaR, Greeks, stress testing)

*Soft Skills:*
- Professional skepticism and critical thinking
- Clear communication (written and verbal)
- Stakeholder management and influence without authority
- Attention to detail
- Time management

*Industry Knowledge:*
- Follow financial markets and understand market risks
- Read about risk management failures (GFC, LTCM, JPM London Whale) to understand importance
- Understand Basel III and regulatory capital framework
- Learn about financial crises and risk management lessons

=== Entry Points

Investment banks and trading firms recruit risk analysts through:
- *Graduate programs*: Formal risk analyst programs at major banks
- *Direct entry*: Specialist roles for experienced candidates
- *Internal transfers*: Moving from trading, quant, or operations into risk

Target degrees: Finance, Mathematics, Statistics, Engineering, Economics. Strong quantitative skills essential. Postgraduate degrees (Masters in Financial Engineering, MFin, MQF) valuable but not required for entry.

Academic performance important (Distinction average+) plus demonstrated interest in markets and risk. Internships in trading, risk, or quantitative roles helpful.

